{
  "name": "ships attack coastal land in-place; no capture from sea (B20)",
  "notes": "4x3, ocean cols 0-1, land cols 2-3. A battleship (sea, attack 18) sits at (1,1) next to a coastal city (2,1) defended by a fortified militia. Civ 1: ships bombard adjacent coastal land units but only LAND units take cities. Cmd 1: the battleship attacks the militia — combat resolves (a win at rngState 1), the defender dies, the ATTACKER STAYS AT SEA (never advances onto land), and the city is NOT captured (still p2). Cmd 2: with the city now undefended, the ship tries to move onto it — rejected impassable (a sea unit cannot enter land, so no capture-from-sea). The hostiles check runs before the domain check, which is what makes attack-in-place work without a code change; this scenario pins that behavior in both engines.",
